# Context

I moved recently to renderToPipeableStream to increase performance of our application.
Nevertheless my work is refused because there the product team doesnâ€™t like the transition effect between the raw html loaded and the moment where the css is finally loaded.

Here is the effect, that the product team wants to avoid : 


https://github.com/facebook/react/assets/21305034/4fb7f950-69b1-4d2e-92c9-3141d91e9815


*For the example, I simulate a slow network but even with fast connection, the transition briefly appears.*


# My code

```typescript
import type { Response } from 'express';
import { renderToPipeableStream } from 'react-dom/server';
import { Helmet } from 'react-helmet';

import App from './MainApp';

export async function render(url: string, res: Response, assets, webMain: string[]) {
  const helmet = Helmet.renderStatic();
  const context = { statusCode: 200 };
  let didError = false;
  const stream = renderToPipeableStream(<App url={url} context={context} assets={assets} helmet={helmet} />, {
    bootstrapScripts: webMain,
    onAllReady: () => {
      res.setHeader('Content-type', 'text/html');
      if (didError) {
        res.status(500);
      } else {
        res.status(context.statusCode || 200);
      }
      stream.pipe(res);
    },
    onError: () => {
      didError = true;
    },
    onShellError: () => {
      didError = true;
    },
  });
}
```

# My question

Is it possible to begin to display something only when we get all the css ? (But to keep the stream strategy for all the js files and keep the hydratation) ?
